<subSubSection pageId="117" pageNumber="513" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="117.[727,1319,685,1112]" lastBlockId="117.[114,1322,1127,2057]" pageId="117" pageNumber="513">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[728,1013,1079,1112]" pageId="117" pageNumber="513">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 77-100 mm, tail 55-68 mm, ear 6-611 mm, hindfoot 13-16 mm; weight 11-15 g. The Ugandan Lowland White-toothed Shrew is a medium-sized shrew. Dorsal pelage is dark brownish gray to slate gray; ventral pelage is slightly paler. Feet are reddish brown to yellowish brown. Tail is relatively long (c.70% of head-body length), slightly bicolored, being dark reddish brown dorsally and slightly lighter ventrally, and covered in long bristle hairs. Skull has a proportionally wide interorbital region; rostrum is moderately robust; the braincase is narrow and flat; the unicusipids are robust and M” is moderately wide. There are three unicuspids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
